===Etymology===
From Old (and modern) French [[peine]], from Latin [[poena]] ‘punishment, pain’.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/peɪn/}}
*{{audio|en-us-pain.ogg|Audio (US)}}
**Homophones: [[pane]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun|pain|pains}}
# ''(countable and uncountable)'' an [[ache]], bodily [[suffering]] or an instance of this; [[hurt]], [[injury]] or unpleasant sensation
# ''(uncountable, obsolete except in set phrases)'' suffering seen as a [[punishment]] or [[penalty]]
#:''You may not leave this room on '''pain''' of death.''
# ''(uncountable)'' the condition or fact of [[suffering]] or [[anguish]], as opposed to [[pleasure]]
#:''In the final analysis, '''pain''' is a fact of life.''
#:''I had to stop running when I started getting '''pains''' in my feet.''
# ''(countable)'' An annoying person or thing.
#:''Your mother is a right '''pain'''.''
# ''(uncountable)'' mental [[suffering]] or [[anguish]], especially sadness or grief
#:''The '''pain''' of departure was difficult to bear.''

